Newer models are promising but not sufficient. They do better with existing data, but are nowhere near AGI.

A more serious discussion can be found with Sutton and Lecunn, who are open about the algorithmic limitations.

Understandable hype from the antrophic CEO...but hype nonetheless.

Viewed OpenAI admits hallucinations are inevitable.

Language models generate text token by token. Each word is a probabilistic guess, not a fact.

But most benchmarks score on correctness instead of confidence. That means models are encouraged to give any possible correct answer to all questions.

Benchmark Question: When is my birthday?
Model: <There are 365 days in a year>
<If I guess something, I have a 1/365 chance of getting it right>
<If I guess nothing, I get a score if ZERO.>
Your birthday is on 1st January.

It's like an entrance exam with no negative score for wrong answers. Any answer is better than no answer.

This encourages hallucinations. The problem is baked into evaluation datasets.

OpenAI is calling for an industry-wide change in benchmarks. 

Future models should be rewarded for admitting uncertainty, instead of random guessing.

Let's see if Google and DeepSeek tag along.

#AI #Hallucinations

When you paste a link into ChatGPT's textbox, it starts loading the page in the background.

The concept isn't new. Instagram does something similar by asking users to add a description while their photos upload in the background. 

Because faster responses lead to better user engagement.

Viewed From Struggles to Strategy: Sharing My Story with the Brilliant Minds at JUIT

Walking into a room full of curious minds is always a privilege‚Äîand my recent visit to the Jaypee University of Information Technology, Waknaghat (JUIT), was no exception.

From the warm welcome by the faculty to the insightful questions from students, everything about the experience reminded me why I love being an educator.

During the session, I spoke about a few topics close to my heart:


My Journey to Becoming an Educator:
I shared the real story‚Äîmy beginnings, the struggles, the lessons. I wanted to show that the path to success isn't always straight, but with patience, persistence, and passion, it‚Äôs definitely worth it.

Why Engineering Mathematics is More Than Just Numbers:
Mathematics is not just a subject‚Äîit‚Äôs a powerful way of thinking. I showed how it helps solve real-world engineering problems and why it's so essential in both academics and industry.

Cracking GATE & Competitive Exams:
We discussed smart strategies for exam prep: concept clarity, solving PYQs, managing time, and most importantly‚Äîstaying consistent. There‚Äôs no magic formula, but there is a method.

Mathematics: The Backbone of Machine Learning:
ML is shaping the future, and at its core lies mathematics. From linear algebra to probability, a strong math foundation makes it much easier to understand and innovate in this space.

But the real highlight?

The students.
Curious, sharp, and driven ‚Äî their questions sparked deeper discussions and made me hopeful for the future.


Thank you once again,Jaypee University of Information Technology, Waknaghat and SIAM JUIT, for the opportunity to share, connect, and grow together.
Looking forward to more such enriching moments.
